      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(auth): Add 1Password keyring backend",
        "body": "Local and agent workflows currently have to choose between OS keychains, which can prompt repeatedly or behave poorly in headless contexts, and the encrypted file backend, which requires distributing `GOG_KEYRING_PASSWORD`. This adds a 1Password-backed option so gog auth material can live in a configured 1Password vault while local desktop workflows can use the 1Password app instead of a service account token.\n\nThis change adds a `1password` keyring backend using the 1Password Go SDK. It supports desktop-app auth through `onepassword_account` / `GOG_1PASSWORD_ACCOUNT`, service-account auth through `OP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_TOKEN`, and vault/item selection through config or environment. 1Password items are API Credential entries titled `gogcli-keyring` by default, with the keyring key in `username` and the encoded payload in the concealed `credential` field.\n\nExample local setup:\n\n```bash\ngog auth keyring 1password\ngog config set onepassword_auth desktop\ngog config set onepassword_account xxx.1password.com\ngog config set onepassword_vault <vault-id>\n```\n\nRepeated short-lived subprocesses can also opt in to a state-dir access-token cache:\n\n```bash\ngog config set access_token_cache true\n```\n\nThe cache stores only short-lived Google access tokens, checks it before reopening the refresh-token keyring, and clears it when stored auth is removed. That keeps agent-style Gmail/Calendar loops from repeatedly asking for 1Password approval while preserving 1Password as the source of truth for refresh tokens.\n\nA couple of guardrails are included for review:\n\n- 1Password only treats tagged `gogcli-keyring` API Credential items as managed, except for an empty starter template that is tagged on first use.\n- `OP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_TOKEN` remains environment-only; non-secret selectors can live in `config.json`.\n- `auth doctor` reports the selected 1Password auth mode and missing vault/account/token configuration.\n",
